have this great video online of... He was 
a VP of product. He was initially masked,  

545
00:46:39,480 --> 00:46:44,840
but VP of product at Nike. I met him through 
Marty and Chris at Silicon Valley Product  

546
00:46:44,840 --> 00:46:49,440
Group. He joined one of our product councils, 
and then he decided to leave. And he was like,  

547
00:46:49,440 --> 00:46:55,560
"Phyl, I love you, but this candidate market 
fit stuff, no. You're wrong. It needs to be  

548
00:46:55,560 --> 00:46:59,880
[inaudible 00:46:57]." And so he went out and he 
actually spoke to a bunch of VCs and like, " We  

549
00:46:59,880 --> 00:47:04,544
don't have any idea what to do with you. You 
have to tell us something really specific."  

550
00:47:04,544 --> 00:47:12,400
He was like, "Oh, man." So he went, he's 
like, "Phyl..." So he redid it, bam, bam, bam. 

551
00:47:12,400 --> 00:47:19,680
I tell another story in the book about Dee. She 
was a chief data officer of a large company in  

552
00:47:19,680 --> 00:47:24,320
tech, wanted to become a CTO. She had a technology 
and engineering background, as well as data. She  

553
00:47:24,320 --> 00:47:28,480
spent a year spinning her wheels alone. I said, 
"Join a job search council." She figured out her  

554
00:47:28,480 --> 00:47:36,320
candidate market fit. It turns out she was a 
great fit for a mid-size regional bank CTO.  

555
00:47:37,200 --> 00:47:43,080
And within three weeks she had three offers. A 
year, nothing. Within three weeks, three offers. 

556
00:47:43,080 --> 00:47:47,360
So I can't guarantee that you're going 
to get three offers within three weeks,  

557
00:47:47,360 --> 00:47:50,320
right? I'm not saying that. Some of you, it 
might take you six months or a year. And the  

558
00:47:50,320 --> 00:47:56,240
more senior you are, Lenny, the longer it is. If 
you're a CEO, it's going to take you a long time,  

559
00:47:56,240 --> 00:48:02,340
unless you happen to be the CEO of Chipotle, 
who just became the CEO of Starbucks.

560
00:48:02,340 --> 00:48:05,720
Yeah. Yeah, I know you're creating a 
page that we're going to link people to,  

561
00:48:05,720 --> 00:48:08,240
which is, I think... Is it phyl.org/lenny?

562
00:48:08,240 --> 00:48:09,040
Yes.

563
00:48:09,040 --> 00:48:13,680
Okay, cool. And is it going to have this 
template to help you work out your market fit?

564
00:48:13,680 --> 00:48:18,800
There'll be a link to where you can download not 
only that template, but all the templates. You  

565
00:48:18,800 --> 00:48:24,280
don't even have to join a job search council 
to get all this stuff. I hope you do. Again,  

566
00:48:24,280 --> 00:48:30,640
it's free. I will say, early on people were 
like, "What's the trick here? This is free,  

567
00:48:30,640 --> 00:48:38,000
and you're going to charge me." No. No, this 
is free. Why am I making it free? Because,  

568
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:44,240
one, I can, which is cool; second, 
this is in honor of my mom; and third,  

569
00:48:44,240 --> 00:48:49,520
I want to create a private safety net for the 
ravages of creative destruction. It's great. A  

570
00:48:49,520 --> 00:48:53,040
lot of positive consequences, but there's 
negative ones. And I just don't love the  

571
00:48:53,040 --> 00:48:58,080
idea of charging people for this. I charge 
people for other things, but not for this.

572
00:48:58,080 --> 00:49:00,720
And we'll link people to the things 
you charge for so they can support  

573
00:49:00,720 --> 00:49:03,960
you and benefit you in other ways, 
or benefit themselves in other ways.

574
00:49:03,960 --> 00:49:07,360
Benefit them and me. That'd be awesome.

575
00:49:07,360 --> 00:49:10,120
Let's talk about some other tactics. You 
mentioned this idea of playing to win,  

576
00:49:10,120 --> 00:49:15,240
and I think within that, there's this kind of 
OKR in mission tactic. Let's talk about that.

577
00:49:15,240 --> 00:49:22,200
50%, Lenny, of the people who read my book, join 
a job search council, and follow everything I've  

578
00:49:22,200 --> 00:49:29,960
described, the people don't do what I'm about 
to tell you, it is the biggest mistake and miss,  

579
00:49:29,960 --> 00:49:36,840
and I'm really sorry about this. I'm on a 
campaign, right? So here's the thing. When  

580
00:49:36,840 --> 00:49:45,400
you start to interview and negotiate, you've got 
to be in charge. This is collaborative coaching.  

581
00:49:45,400 --> 00:49:50,320
I want you to play to win, not to lose.
Now, when people hear me say that, they  

582
00:49:50,320 --> 00:49:57,000
translate it in their brains into, "Oh, Phyl is 
saying that I've got to be a ruthless negotiator."  

583
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:07,480
If anyone who knows me know that ruthless is 
just not how I am, at least in this sense. No,  

584
00:50:07,480 --> 00:50:14,680
no, I'm like, "What I want you to do," and it's a 
great tactic that we stumbled upon, and it's one  

585
00:50:14,680 --> 00:50:20,120
of the best tactics in the book, and I really hope 
we can get the other half of the people who are in  

586
00:50:20,120 --> 00:50:26,760
the community to do this, and your listeners who 
aren't involved who decide to join also do this,  

587
00:50:26,760 --> 00:50:31,920
when you start interviewing, I want you to create 
your own version of the job description. I want  

588
00:50:31,920 --> 00:50:37,800
you to do it privately, Lenny, and I want you 
to create what I call a job mission with OKRs. 

589
00:50:37,800 --> 00:50:44,120
Now, most job descriptions, they suck, Lenny. The 
company doesn't know what the eff they're doing.  

590
00:50:44,120 --> 00:50:50,560
They don't know exactly what they're looking 
for. But I'm not telling you to say that to them,  

591
00:50:50,560 --> 00:50:54,920
just to be clear. I'm telling you, "I 
want you to create your own job mission  

592
00:50:54,920 --> 00:51:00,760
with OKRs." This is key. It needs to be with 
OKRs. Now, your audience knows what an OKR is,  

593
00:51:00,760 --> 00:51:04,640
objectives and key results, and I assume I 
don't need to explain that. It needs to be  

594
00:51:04,640 --> 00:51:08,280
something where you are saying, "Here's 
what I think I'm going to be accountable  

595
00:51:08,280 --> 00:51:13,120
for. Here's what I'm going to actually... 
the outcomes I'm going to deliver," right?

596
00:51:13,120 --> 00:51:14,480
At the company that you join.

597
00:51:14,480 --> 00:51:19,480
At the company you join. Now, you'll keep it 
private at first because drafting it... This  

598
00:51:19,480 --> 00:51:25,200
thing has multiple benefits. The first is drafting 
it will help you understand and develop great  

599
00:51:25,200 --> 00:51:31,360
interview questions to ask them to clarify, 
what is this job? And they'll be impressed by  

600
00:51:31,360 --> 00:51:36,400
that. Okay? The second thing is, once you've had 
a couple of interviews, and it's a draft... Now,  

601
00:51:36,400 --> 00:51:40,720
it's not a full, final thing. This is so 
important. I want you to pull the hiring  

602
00:51:40,720 --> 00:51:45,520
manager aside and say, "Hey, Lenny, you're the 
hiring manager. I've thought about what the role  

603
00:51:45,520 --> 00:51:50,040
is. I want to make sure I'm understanding it 
correctly. Can I share something with you?"  

604
00:51:50,040 --> 00:51:54,640
I don't want you to email it. I want you to 
do phone call, Zoom, or coffee or whatever. 

605
00:51:54,640 --> 00:52:02,080
Lenny, can you imagine how hiring managers feel 
when they get this job mission with OKRs? I was  

606
00:52:02,080 --> 00:52:06,440
talking to a senior guy at Amazon who's hired more 
than 2000 product leaders and others. He said,  

607
00:52:06,440 --> 00:52:12,640
"Phyl, no one in..." He's part of our product 
account. He said, "No one in my life has ever  

608
00:52:12,640 --> 00:52:19,080
done this. If someone did this, it would blow my 
mind. I would hire them on the spot." And that's  

609
00:52:19,080 --> 00:52:25,400
the message I want these folks to understand.
We talk about silver medals, Lenny. In the  

610
00:52:25,400 --> 00:52:29,160
job search, the silver medal sucks. At the 
Olympics, hey, it's pretty good. You get to  

611
00:52:29,160 --> 00:52:34,240
be on the podium. But guess what? Silver medal 
is... It's almost worse than... Because you were  

612
00:52:34,240 --> 00:52:38,680
almost there. And we have a number of videos and 
other things where we talk about the difference,  

613
00:52:38,680 --> 00:52:42,520
in many cases, between getting the 
silver and gold has been doing the job  

614
00:52:42,520 --> 00:52:49,480
mission with OKRs. Companies say, "This is what 
distinguished you. This is what..." We were like,  

615
00:52:49,480 --> 00:52:53,560
"Who is this person?" They're already thinking 
about what they're accountable and the outcomes,  

616
00:52:53,560 --> 00:52:57,840
and naturally they're thinking about it 
better than I am, which is fantastic,  

617
00:52:57,840 --> 00:53:02,040
right? So it raises the odds, but it 
also does something if you present it... 

618
00:53:02,040 --> 00:53:06,160
Again, Lenny, you're the hiring manager. I 
show you my job mission OKRs, and you're like,  

619
00:53:06,160 --> 00:53:10,080
"Oh, this is fantastic," but you also say, 
"Oh, this thing you have here, this OKR,  

620
00:53:10,080 --> 00:53:14,520
this isn't part of the role. Well, that's 
helpful to understand, but this thing that  

621
00:53:14,520 --> 00:53:19,400
you don't have listed is." "Oh, really?" Lenny, 
how many times... I'm going to ask people in the  

622
00:53:19,400 --> 00:53:26,440
audience to raise their hands. How many times have 
you taken the job A that turned out to be job B?  

623
00:53:27,920 --> 00:53:33,440
Everybody just raised their hands, Lenny. 
So this helps to address that, right? 

624
00:53:35,160 --> 00:53:40,160
And then if you get the offer, and again, 
this raises the odds of getting the offer,  

625
00:53:40,160 --> 00:53:46,560
it then sets you up to negotiate what I call 
the four legs of the negotiations tool. This  

626
00:53:46,560 --> 00:53:52,680
is not hard negotiation. This is something the 
company loves. I actually say, you get an offer  

627
00:53:52,680 --> 00:53:59,120
and it's like whatever, $250,000 base with a 
30% bonus. This may be a director or whatever,  

628
00:53:59,120 --> 00:54:07,440
or senior manager. Maybe it's an 800 base if 
you're more senior, whatever it might be. I  

629
00:54:07,440 --> 00:54:14,160
want you to go and talk to the hiring manager, if 
possible. Hopefully not the recruiter. We'll talk  

630
00:54:14,160 --> 00:54:21,240
about that. And I want you to say, "This is great. 
I want to talk about money, but before we do,  

631
00:54:21,240 --> 00:54:26,160
I want to think about some of the things that 
will set me up to see succeed in this role.  

632
00:54:26,960 --> 00:54:33,920
I think there's like $10 million of tech debt 
here. Does that sound right to you? And are we  

633
00:54:33,920 --> 00:54:39,640
on board that that'll be priority one to 
eliminate the first day I start the job?" 

634
00:54:39,640 --> 00:54:45,480
We had two CPOs, both interviewing at private 
equity firms, private equity-owned companies,  

635
00:54:45,480 --> 00:54:50,440
about the same size, SaaS companies. One had tech 
debt of 20 million, one had tech debt of 10. I  

636
00:54:50,440 --> 00:54:56,520
told them both, "You got to talk about that in 
the..." So one talked about it in the negotiation,  

637
00:54:56,520 --> 00:55:00,560
and the company was like, "Oh, that's great." 
They wrote a check on day one. Six months later,  

638
00:55:00,560 --> 00:55:04,880
the tech debt was relieved. They updated 
the systems. They were able to get into  

639
00:55:04,880 --> 00:55:09,600
innovation. A year later, they got promoted 
to a GM role in addition to their CPO role,  

640
00:55:09,600 --> 00:55:15,240
and then a year after that, they were being 
interviewed for the CEO role. The other person,  

641
00:55:15,240 --> 00:55:20,560
where there was 10 million of tech debt, was kind 
shy about asking, sort of mentioned it, they were  

642
00:55:20,560 --> 00:55:24,920
like, "Oh, we'll talk about it when you get here," 
but they didn't really commit, and they never  

643
00:55:24,920 --> 00:55:30,720
addressed it. One month, six months, 12 months, 18 
months later, he's looking for a job. This is the  

644
00:55:30,720 --> 00:55:37,040
opportunity cost of not being set up for success.
Now, again, don't hear this as antagonistic. We're  

645
00:55:37,040 --> 00:55:42,040
not antagonistic here. We're trying to say, 
"What's going to help me succeed?" So one CPO  

646
00:55:42,040 --> 00:55:48,480
recently was negotiating... I'm not just talking 
about budget for tech debt or whatever. If you're  

647
00:55:48,480 --> 00:55:54,000
a senior person, do you think that team needs more 
training? Do you need to send them over to Marty's  

648
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:00,360
workshops, over to my product councils, right? Get 
them into Lenny's community. The company was like,  

649
00:56:00,360 --> 00:56:03,961
"You're negotiating the training budget 
of the team that you don't even run yet-"

650
00:56:03,961 --> 00:56:04,680
You're negotiating the training budget of the team 
that you don't even run yet while we're talking  

651
00:56:04,680 --> 00:56:10,920
about your salary? Who are you? We love you, 
we're going to pay you even more. Lenny,  

652
00:56:10,920 --> 00:56:16,080
companies love this. And even if you're a junior 
person, you're not going to negotiate budget,  

653
00:56:16,080 --> 00:56:22,120
but you can talk about mentorship, professional 
development, will you be able to attend  

654
00:56:22,120 --> 00:56:28,800
conferences or training? Again, and this is, we're 
not hard negotiating this, we're saying, "Here's  

655
00:56:28,800 --> 00:56:32,840
what I think I'm going to need to accomplish 
the OKRs that we've already agreed upon."

656
00:56:32,840 --> 00:56:36,760
This is really cool advice, I want to make sure 
people super understand it. So an example of tech  

657
00:56:36,760 --> 00:56:42,520
debt. This person asked, "I need $10 million 
budget in order to address this tech debt."

658
00:56:42,520 --> 00:56:43,440
Yeah.

659
00:56:43,440 --> 00:56:47,760
I see. So it's not like, "I believe we will save 
$10 million if we spend on time." It's like,  

660
00:56:47,760 --> 00:56:50,680
"Here's how much this team will need 
and I will need to be successful."

661
00:56:50,680 --> 00:56:54,240
I'm going to need a check 
for $10 million on day one.

662
00:56:54,240 --> 00:56:57,760
I guess you're right, someone 
would be shy asking for that.  

663
00:56:57,760 --> 00:57:00,040
Or that was $20 million actually, 
that was the one that asked for it.

664
00:57:00,040 --> 00:57:05,200
That was the 20 million, that was right. And 
again, it was not... Yes, people feel really  

665
00:57:05,200 --> 00:57:11,520
shy about this, but the companies love that 
they understood what it was going to take.  

666
00:57:12,360 --> 00:57:17,920
I will tell you what, if the company doesn't 
like this, it's a huge red flag. Huge red flag,  

667
00:57:17,920 --> 00:57:23,160
it means they're not serious. But if you're 
talking to them, "Hey, I think we're going to  

668
00:57:23,160 --> 00:57:31,720
need train the team. I'm going to need to hire 
three more ICs," or the design function is weak,  

669
00:57:31,720 --> 00:57:36,280
or whatever it might be. And then you're 
like, "Do you agree? Do you see it this way?" 

670
00:57:37,440 --> 00:57:41,640
And they're like, "Yeah, that's right. 
Good. Wow." You're already like bang,  

671
00:57:41,640 --> 00:57:49,280
bang, bang. We haven't even finished negotiating 
your salary. And this is so counterintuitive,  

672
00:57:49,280 --> 00:57:57,120
Lenny. I'm the queen of counterintuitive 
stuff. Kelly Marcus said it's counterintuitive,  

673
00:57:57,120 --> 00:58:04,000
right? But this is as well. People think they're 
going to lose the opportunity when it actually  

674
00:58:04,000 --> 00:58:08,840
wins them. Now, of course, if they marched in 
and said, "Damn it, you have to do X and Y,"  

675
00:58:08,840 --> 00:58:12,440
right? That's not what I'm talking about.
"Hey, here's how I see it. This is the  

676
00:58:12,440 --> 00:58:16,440
OKRs. I think we're going to need this. 
Does that make sense to you?" And you're  

677
00:58:16,440 --> 00:58:21,320
having a collaborative conversation about 
how you need to be set up for success. 

678
00:58:21,320 --> 00:58:26,800
And by the way, if they say, "No, I hear you. I 
believe you, but no," then you make a judgment  

679
00:58:26,800 --> 00:58:32,760
decision. I'm not always saying you turn that 
away. Well, especially if you need a job,  

680
00:58:32,760 --> 00:58:37,080
but you're now going in eyes wide open. 
You are not going to be able to believe  

681
00:58:37,080 --> 00:58:41,320
that tech debt initially. You're going 
to have to work within that constraint.

682
00:58:41,320 --> 00:58:44,320
So I love that we're getting into negotiation 
advice by the way, because I was hoping we'd  

683
00:58:44,320 --> 00:58:50,000
get there. So the advice here is identify 
something that you'll need to be successful,  

684
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:55,680
and your finding is that when you ask for, 
and it seems like a financial investment  

685
00:58:55,680 --> 00:59:00,120
as a part of you joining, ends up 
leading to a better comp for you.

686
00:59:00,120 --> 00:59:05,440
Yes, and I will say that there's less negotiating 
room today than there was two years ago because of  

687
00:59:05,440 --> 00:59:11,800
the market that we're in. And the data all bears 
that out, and we see that. But here's the other  

688
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:16,520
piece of data. So I want you to ask for things 
that tie back to the OKRs that you've already  

689
00:59:16,520 --> 00:59:21,840
agreed on with the hiring manager. This is how 
this thing connects together, right? It's like  

690
00:59:21,840 --> 00:59:29,520
Legos, and then we come to the money and you've 
had this lovely conversation. You've shown them  

691
00:59:29,520 --> 00:59:35,480
how much you're invested in succeeding. See, 
Lenny, the problem that every hiring manager  

692
00:59:35,480 --> 00:59:41,920
has is distinguishing be someone between someone 
who is a good talker, and someone who can actually  

693
00:59:41,920 --> 00:59:50,280
make things happen. You know this, right? And this 
is true every from individual contributor to CEO. 

694
00:59:50,280 --> 00:59:55,560
By doing the job mission of the OKRs, and by 
showing them that draft, you are showing them.  

695
00:59:55,560 --> 00:59:59,840
Not telling them, showing them that you 
take initiative, that you're accountable,  

696
00:59:59,840 --> 01:00:04,840
that you can make things happen. And then in 
the salary negotiation, by talking to them  

697
01:00:04,840 --> 01:00:09,800
about what you need to succeed, you're showing 
them that you really want to succeed. And guess  

698
01:00:09,800 --> 01:00:15,440
who that benefits? That benefits the company, 
obviously. I want you to do that first and then,  

699
01:00:15,440 --> 01:00:20,800
okay, so then let's talk money. Now, 87% of 
the time, Lenny, when you ask for more money,  

700
01:00:20,800 --> 01:00:29,360
you get it. Now, that's a longitudinal statistic, 
meaning over many years. It's going to be lower  

701
01:00:29,360 --> 01:00:37,240
in a moment like this, but you can still 
ask, and people are afraid to ask. Again,  

702
01:00:37,240 --> 01:00:44,480
don't ask in some shark way like some of 
my friends in business might do. Some M&A  

703
01:00:44,480 --> 01:00:51,400
negotiators, whatever. No, ask, are you open?
Unless it's a deal breaker. If it's a deal  

704
01:00:51,400 --> 01:00:56,240
breaker, just be open about that. But if it's not, 
let's say they offered you whatever it is. 400  

705
01:00:56,240 --> 01:01:02,920
base with up to 100% whatever in some RSUs 
or options, blah, blah, and you really wanted  

706
01:01:02,920 --> 01:01:10,160
450. Lenny, you can say, "Hey, are you open 
to 450? That was really what I was hoping  

707
01:01:10,160 --> 01:01:16,040
for. What I think I'm worth, are you open to 
that? Is that something we can talk about?" 

708
01:01:16,040 --> 01:01:20,880
And most of the time they say yes. They may not 
get you to 450. They may be like, "You know what?  

709
01:01:20,880 --> 01:01:27,840
Yes, thank you. Let me get back to you." Or, 
"No, we could go to 420. Does that work? Great."

710
01:01:27,840 --> 01:01:29,440
You make it sound very easy.

711
01:01:30,160 --> 01:01:30,640
Here's the thing-

712
01:01:30,640 --> 01:01:32,320
I hate negotiating. Yeah, go.

713
01:01:32,320 --> 01:01:35,480
I do too. And I talk about this 
in the book and Jason Fried,  

714
01:01:35,480 --> 01:01:41,240
who you know. Jason Fried's got this great 
thing where they have all very clear bans,  

715
01:01:41,920 --> 01:01:45,760
37signals, well, at Basecamp. He's like, 
"Because no one's trained in negotiation,  

716
01:01:45,760 --> 01:01:49,960
how can we expect people to negotiate?" And 
there's another thing Marty says about my book.  

717
01:01:49,960 --> 01:01:54,160
He says what he loves is that companies 
have all of these resources. They've got  

718
01:01:54,160 --> 01:01:59,440
lawyers and HR people, and you're there alone.
That's why you need your job search council.  

719
01:01:59,440 --> 01:02:03,600
This is when you really need to ask for help 
because every bone in your body is going to say,  

720
01:02:03,600 --> 01:02:10,080
"I'm not going to negotiate. That's going to make 
it worse," and it almost never does. And again,  

